  <div class="container">
    <div class="header">
      <h1>WORLDWIDE INDIGENOUS NUMERAL SYSTEMS</h1>
      <h2>A Global Atlas of Language-Native Counting Systems</h2>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.2rem; color: #FFD700; font-weight: 700;">Universal Hyperdimensional Numeric Engine</h2>
      <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; color: #FFD700; margin-top: 8px; font-weight: 600;">The operating platform for language-independent numeric systems</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.82rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); margin-top: 10px;">Published by the Universal Hyperdimensional Numeric Engine Research Initiative<br><strong style="color: rgba(255,215,0,0.85);">Version 1.0 &middot; 2026 Public Release</strong></p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.82rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.65); margin-top: 8px;">Designed for researchers, educators, software developers, and digital humanities scholars.</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; opacity: 0.85; margin-top: 10px; font-style: italic; text-align: justify; line-height: 1.7;">A living atlas of the world&rsquo;s indigenous numeral systems, implemented on the Universal Hyperdimensional Numeric Engine. Each language receives a complete, open-access numerical index &mdash; standardized, searchable, and computationally equipped for a global adventure &mdash; beginning with the 833-entry Yor&ugrave;b&aacute; master table and expanding to host every indigenous and underrepresented numeric tradition. This module contributes to linguistic equity, computational sovereignty, and open scholarly infrastructure for global knowledge preservation.</p>
    </div>

